definitions.definition: moving or appearing to move away from a particular place, especially one that is enclosed or hidden.
examples: he walked out into the street

definitions.definition: situated or operating in the open air, not in buildings.
examples: the search-and-rescue team have been out looking for you

definitions.definition: no longer detained in custody or in jail.
examples: they would be out on bail in no time

definitions.definition: situated far or at a particular distance from somewhere.
examples: an old farmhouse right out in the middle of nowhere

definitions.definition: to sea, away from the land.
examples: the fleet put out from Cyprus

definitions.definition: (of the tide) falling or at its lowest level.
examples: the tide was going out

definitions.definition: away from home.
examples: he's gone out

definitions.definition: in a public place for purposes of pleasure or entertainment.
examples: an evening out at a restaurant

definitions.definition: indicating a specified distance away from the goal line or finishing line.
examples: he scored from 70 meters out

definitions.definition: so as to be revealed or known.
examples: find out what you can

definitions.definition: aloud; so as to be heard.
examples: Miss Beard cried out in horror

definitions.definition: at or to an end.
examples: the romance fizzled out

definitions.definition: so as to be finished or complete.
examples: I'll leave them to fight it out

definitions.definition: (in various other completive uses).
examples: the crowd had thinned out

definitions.definition: (of a light or fire) so as to be extinguished or no longer burning.
examples: at ten o'clock the lights went out

definitions.definition: (of a stain or mark) no longer visible; removed.
examples: try to get the stain out

definitions.definition: (of a party, politician, etc.) not in office.
(of a jury) considering its verdict in secrecy.
through to the outside.
examples: he ran out the door

definitions.definition: not at home or at one's place of work.
examples: if he called, she'd pretend to be out

definitions.definition: revealed or made public.
examples: the secret was soon out

definitions.definition: (of a flower) in bloom; open.
examples: in flower, flowering, in (full) bloom, blooming, in blossom, blossoming, open the roses are out

definitions.definition: published.
examples: the book should be out before the end of the month
synonyms: in print "the book should be out soon"

definitions.definition: in existence or in use.
examples: it works as well as any system that's out

definitions.definition: not concealing one's homosexuality.
examples: I had been out since I was seventeen

definitions.definition: no longer alight; extinguished.
examples: the fire was nearly out
synonyms: no longer alight "the fire was nearly out"

definitions.definition: at an end.
examples: school was out for the summer

definitions.definition: no longer in fashion.
examples: life in the fast lane is out

definitions.definition: not possible or worth considering.
examples: a trip to the seaside is out

definitions.definition: in a state of unconsciousness.
unable to rise before the count of ten.
mistaken; in error.
examples: he was slightly out in his calculations

definitions.definition: (of the ball in tennis and similar games) outside the designated playing area.
no longer batting or on base, having had one's turn ended by the team in the field.
examples: the Yankees are out in the ninth

definitions.definition: a way of escaping from a problem or dilemma.
examples: he was desperately looking for an out

definitions.definition: an act of putting a player out.
the political party or politicians not in office.
come or go out; emerge.
examples: the truth will out

definitions.definition: reveal the homosexuality of (a prominent person).
examples: expose, unmask it was not our intention to out him

definitions.definition: to the point of surpassing or exceeding.
examples: outfight

definitions.definition: external; separate; from outside.
examples: outbuildings

definitions.definition: away from; outward.
examples: outbound
